  "editorial": {
    "headline": "Durbin Walks Off Yankees for Boston in Ten Innings",
    "subheadline": "Dramatic Finish in the 10th Innings Lifts Boston Red Sox",
    "lead_angle": "Caleb Durbin slapped a single past a drawn-in infield to score Jarren Duran from third, delivering the Boston Red Sox a 5-4 victory over the New York Yankees. The Fenway crowd erupted as Durbin’s liner found right field grass in the tenth inning, capping a frantic three-run rally. The hit came off losing pitcher Fernando Cruz, who inherited a two-run lead in the bottom half and could not escape a bases-loaded, one-out jam.\n\nNew York forced the extra frame by erasing a two-run deficit in the ninth. After being silenced for eight innings, the Yankees finally broke through against the Boston bullpen. Amed Rosario delivered a run-scoring single and Anthony Volpe drew a bases-loaded walk to tie the game. The rally spoiled a dominant performance from starter Sonny Gray, who mowed down New York hitters for 7.1 shutout innings, striking out nine and allowing just three hits.\n\nDurbin delivered Boston’s biggest moments. His sacrifice fly in the fourth inning scored the game’s first run, and his tenth-inning single walked it off. He finished just 1-for-4, but his two runs batted in were the most crucial of the night. The win has immediate playoff implications, pulling Boston closer to division-leading New York. Justin Slaten earned the victory after pitching a scoreless top of the tenth.",
    "reason": "Extra-inning walk-off — the purest combination of tension and resolution the sport offers."
